4. Input Schema Specification

VORIN‑Ω accepts exactly four fields:

AREA: 
PROBLEM: 
REQUEST: 
DOMAIN: 

DOMAIN is optional but recommended.

4.1 Field Definitions

AREA
Defines the physical, conceptual, or logical location of the issue.

PROBLEM
Describes the explicit issue or state requiring attention.

REQUEST
Defines the action the user wants Omricon to perform.

DOMAIN
Specifies the operational domain for routing and validation.

4.2 Field Constraints

AREA: 1 to 80 characters
PROBLEM: 1 to 200 characters
REQUEST: 1 to 200 characters
DOMAIN: 1 to 40 characters
Encoding: UTF‑8
Invalid characters: { } [ ] < > |

---

5. System Architecture

VORIN‑Ω consists of five deterministic stages:

1. Field Validator
2. Semantic Mapper
3. Compatibility Checker
4. Payload Assembler
5. Cross‑Level Normalisation


Each stage is mandatory and failure‑blocking.

---

6. Stage Descriptions

6.1 Field Validator

Purpose: Ensure the input conforms to the schema.

Checks performed:

• all required fields present
• fields non‑empty
• valid characters
• correct ordering
• no duplicate fields
• no malformed prefixes

Failure conditions:

• missing field
• empty field
• invalid characters
• schema mismatch

Output: validated field set.

---

6.2 Semantic Mapper

Purpose: Convert validated fields into internal Omricon units.

Mappings:

AREA → context_unit
PROBLEM → meaning_unit
REQUEST → action_unit
DOMAIN → domain_indicator

No transformation or inference is performed.

Output: semantic object.

---

6.3 Compatibility Checker

Purpose: Ensure internal consistency.

Checks:

• AREA and PROBLEM compatibility
• REQUEST and DOMAIN compatibility
• logical coherence
• no mutually exclusive operations
• no contradictory states

Failure conditions:

• incompatible area/problem
• incompatible request/domain
• contradiction detected

Output: validated semantic object.

---

6.4 Payload Assembler

Purpose: Construct the final Omricon payload.

Payload fields:

context_unit
meaning_unit
action_unit
domain_indicator
constraints
ambiguity_flags
contradiction_flags
confidence (always 1.0)

Payload must be deterministic and reproducible.

---

6.5 Cross‑Level Normalisation

Purpose: Ensure compatibility across all O‑levels.

Normalisation ensures:

• O1 receives minimal units
• O2 receives structured meaning/action/context
• O3 receives domain routing data
• O4 receives planning objectives
• O‑Prime receives contradiction‑checking data
• O‑Core receives kernel‑safe structures

This is the defining feature of VORIN‑Ω.

---

7. Data Flow Description

Input → Validator → Mapper → Checker → Assembler → Normaliser → Omricon Core

Each stage produces a deterministic output consumed by the next stage.

No stage performs inference.
No stage modifies user intent.
No stage reorders or rewrites content.

---

8. Error Handling

All errors must be:

• deterministic
• reproducible
• field‑specific
• schema‑specific

Error object fields:

type
reason
field
expected_format

No ambiguous or generic errors are permitted.

